\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\fs32 Preprocessor\cf2\b0\f1\fs20 
\par 
\par \cf0\lang1031\f2 Th\lang2057\f3 is page \cf2\f0 of the JCF Format Settings controls preprocessor handling. Uncheck \b enabled \b0 for behaviour identical to previous versions.
\par 
\par The preprocessor in Delphi is a set of symbols that start with \f4\{$\f0  and are used to turn on or turn off compilation or certain parts of the source. The preprocessor happens before the Delphi compiler, and is not part of the Object-Pascal syntax. This can be proved simply, as the following code compiles:
\par 
\par \cf0\f4\{$IFDEF I_AM_NOT_DEFINED\}\cf2 
\par   this is not object-pascal.
\par \{$ENDIF\}\f0 
\par \f1 
\par \f0 so clearly the text between the ($IFDEF ... and \{$ENDIF\} is not parsed. However the preprocessor is not usually used like this. More commonly it has uses such as platform-dependant code, e.g.
\par 
\par \f4 uses
\par \{$IFDEF MSWINDOWS\}
\par Windows,
\par \{$ENDIF\}
\par \{$IFDEF LINUX\}
\par Types,
\par Libc,
\par \{$ENDIF\}
\par SysConst;\f0 
\par \f1 
\par \f0 The code has well-formed structure even when the preprocessor directives are treated as regular comments. It is recommended that you write code that follows that rule. However much existing code does not do this, and does not make sense if the preprocessor directives are ignored.
\par 
\par e.g.
\par \f4 Function foo;
\par begin
\par \{$IFDEF MSWINDOWS\}
\par 
\par   ...
\par end;
\par \{$ENDIF\}
\par \{$IFDEF LINUX\}
\par 
\par   ...
\par end;
\par \{$ENDIF\}
\par \f0  
\par Removing the directives yeilds code that will not parse:
\par 
\par \f4 Function foo;
\par begin
\par   ...
\par end;
\par   ...
\par end;
\par \f0  \f1 
\par 
\par \b\f0 Enable\b0 : Turn this off if you are not having any problems with the preprocessor at all. This will cause the JCF to behave as all previous versions and not notice the preprocessor directives. The formatter will attempt to parse and format all of the source code. 
\par 
\par Turn this option on if you are having parsing problems caused by preprocessor-related code. In this case, only parts of the code will be formatted, and parts that are excluded by the preprocessor will not be.  
\par 
\par You should enter the symbols defined and the options defined so that the formatter will know which preprocessor-delimited blocks to parse and which to ignore. Note that for the options, they must be entered in the form thatyou use them. E.g. if you use the preprocessor switch \f4\{$IFOPT R+\}\f0 , then the option \f4 R+\f0  must bge entered, the synonym \f4 RANGECHECK \f0 is not sufficient.
\par 
\par The \f4\{$IFDEF\f0 , \f4\{$IFNDEF\f0  and \f4\{$IFOPT\f0  directives are suported, and the new and more flexible \f4\{$IF\f0  directive is partly supported, with simple expressions working. \f4\{$DEFINE\f0  and \f4\{$UNDEF\f0  directives will be recognised and will change the working set of defined sysmbols, but only in the source file in which they are encountered.
\par 
\par 
\par }
